#The script will query the Sentinel Hub API via various criteria (collection date, cloud cover %, etc.),
#that fall within, or touch a user-provided area of interest. The script will return a list of all
#qualifying images for the given query paramters, and then can download the designated Sentinel tile Dataset.
#Once downloaded, the script will apply NDWI classification / stretching to the data for further analysis.

 
#Rex Robichaux, Virginia DEQ, February, 2021.
#Import required dependencies - install all if not already installed in local environment. Due to dependency conflicts
#I have found it nearly impossible to get all of these packages to install and play nicely with an active ArcGIS Python
#3.x install. Therefore, I suggest installing Vanilla Anaconda and setting up a new/empty environment, dedicated to
#geospatial analysis with just the packages listed below.

#Enter Sentinelhub API Query parameters. Here we are searching for all June, 2020 Sentinel 2 imagery with 0-5%
#for the Level 2-A processing level. We then display the qualifying records in a dataframe for manual selection sorted
#ascending by cloud cover percentage.

products = api.query(footprint,
                    date = ('20200601', '20200615'),
                    platformname = 'Sentinel-2',
                    processinglevel = 'Level-2A',
                    cloudcoverpercentage = (0,3))

products_df = api.to_dataframe(products)
products_df_sorted = products_df.sort_values(['cloudcoverpercentage'], ascending=[True])
products_df_sorted

#Time to shop around. Below, we plot the footprints / boundaries for the qualifying Sentinel tiles that met our query criteria.
#The top plot shows all available tiles with their unique ID that can be used for download. The bottom plot shows the footprints
#contrasted with the AOI boundary we identified earlier so that we can pick the most appropriate images.

areas = api.to_geodataframe(products)
ax = areas.plot(column='uuid', cmap=None, figsize=(20, 20))
areas.apply(lambda x: ax.annotate(s=x.uuid, xy=x.geometry.centroid.coords[0], ha='center'),axis=1)

gdf2 = gpd.read_file(boundsdata)
f, ax = plt.subplots(1)
areas.plot(ax=ax,column='uuid',cmap=None,)
gdf2.plot(ax=ax, column='GRID_ID', figsize=(20,20))
plt.show()

#You will need to unzip all of the data to the directory of your choice. Here, we have extracted all contents to a folder
# under D:\ImageClassification\. The folder structure of this data can be intimidating, see the R10 variable below for the
#location of the 10m sensor band data.

#load in the bands of potential interest for usage. Sentinel2 bands are as follows: https://s3.amazonaws.com/content.satimagingcorp.com/media/cms_page_media/1530/image001.png
#The below loads in all channels needed for RGB, NDVI and NDWI classification (bands 2,3,4 and 8). 

R10 = r'D:\ImageClassification\S2B_MSIL2A_20200607T155819_N0214_R097_T18STH_20200607T200319.SAFE\GRANULE\L2A_T18STH_A016997_20200607T161233\IMG_DATA\R10m'
b4 = rio.open(R10+'\T18STH_20200607T155819_B04_10m.jp2')
b3 = rio.open(R10+'\T18STH_20200607T155819_B03_10m.jp2')
b2 = rio.open(R10+'\T18STH_20200607T155819_B02_10m.jp2')
b8 = rio.open(R10+'\T18STH_20200607T155819_B08_10m.jp2')


# Create an RGBNir image for preview 
with rio.open('RGBNir.tiff','w',driver='Gtiff', width=b4.width, height=b4.height, 
              count=4,crs=b4.crs,transform=b4.transform, dtype=b4.dtypes[0]) as rgb:
    rgb.write(b2.read(1),1) 
    rgb.write(b3.read(1),2) 
    rgb.write(b4.read(1),3)
    rgb.write(b8.read(1),4)
    rgb.close()
    
fp = r'RGBNir.tiff'
img = rio.open(fp)
show(img)
print(img.meta)

ndvi=np.where(
    (nir+red)==0., 
    0, 
    (nir-red)/(nir+red))
